50|$|Isingolwani (colourful neck hoops) {{are made}} by winding grass into a <b>hoop,</b> <b>binding</b> it tightly with cotton and decorating it with beads. In order to {{preserve}} the grass and to enable the hoop to retain its shape and hardness, the hoop is boiled in sugar water and left {{in the hot sun}} for a few days. A further outstanding characteristic of the Ndebele is their beadwork. Beadwork is intricate and time-consuming and requires a deft hand and good eyesight. This pastime has long been a social practice in which the women engaged after their chores were finished but today, many projects involve the production of these items for sale to the public.|$|E

